 What kind of justice would Clarence Thomas, President Bush's nominee to fill the Supreme Court seat vacated by Thurgood Marshall, be?
 In a series of interviews with me a few weeks prior to his nomination, Mr.
 Thomas echoed themes that run through his articles and speeches over the past decade. -- "I don't believe in quotas.
 America was founded on a philosophy of individual rights, not group rights.
 But I believe in compensation for actual victims, not for people whose only claim to victimization is that they are members of a historically oppressed group." -- "America should not fall into the trap of blaming all the problems faced by blacks or other minorities on others.
